WEBVTT

00:15.520 --> 00:27.980
XVI CURSED, CURSED CREATOR! Why did I live? Why in that instant did I not extinguish the

00:27.980 --> 00:35.800
spark of existence which you had so wantonly bestowed? I know not. Despair had not yet

00:35.800 --> 00:42.920
taken possession of me. My feelings were those of rage and revenge. I could with pleasure

00:42.920 --> 00:48.300
have destroyed the cottage and its inhabitants, and have glutted myself with their shrieks

00:48.300 --> 00:55.960
and misery. When night came I quitted my retreat and wandered in the wood, and now no longer

00:56.680 --> 01:04.680
of discovery. I gave vent to my anguish and fearful howlings. I was like a wild beast

01:04.680 --> 01:09.720
that had broken the toils, destroying the objects that obstructed me and ranging through

01:09.720 --> 01:18.740
the wood with a stag-like swiftness. Oh, what a miserable night I passed! The cold stars

01:18.740 --> 01:25.480
shone in mockery, and the bare trees waved their branches above me. Now and then the

01:25.480 --> 01:34.000
sweet voice of a bird burst forth amidst the universal stillness. All save I were at rest

01:34.000 --> 01:43.180
or in enjoyment. I, like the arch-fiend, bore a hell within me, and finding myself unsympathized

01:43.180 --> 01:49.700
with, wished to tear up the trees, spread havoc and destruction around me, and then

01:49.700 --> 01:57.020
to have sat down and enjoyed the ruin. But this was a luxury of sensation that could

01:57.020 --> 02:02.800
not endure. I became fatigued with excessive bodily exertion and sank on the damp grass

02:02.800 --> 02:09.960
in the sick impotence of despair. There was none among the myriads of men that existed

02:09.960 --> 02:17.440
who would pity or assist me. And should I feel kindness towards my enemies? No, from

02:17.440 --> 02:23.960
that moment I declared everlasting war against the species, and more than all against him

02:23.960 --> 02:33.780
who had formed me and sent me forth to this insupportable misery. The sun rose. I heard

02:33.780 --> 02:39.400
the voices of men and knew that it was impossible to return to my retreat during that day. Accordingly

02:39.400 --> 02:45.080
I hid myself in some thick underwood, determining to devote the ensuing hours to reflection

02:45.080 --> 02:52.860
on my situation. The pleasant sunshine and the pure air of day restored me to some degree

02:52.860 --> 02:58.240
of tranquility, and when I considered what had passed at the cottage, I could not help

02:58.240 --> 03:04.940
believing that I had been too hasty in my conclusions. I had certainly acted imprudently.

03:04.940 --> 03:10.340
It was apparent that my conversation had interested the father on my behalf, and I was a fool

03:10.340 --> 03:16.380
in having exposed my person to the horror of his children. I ought to have familiarized

03:16.380 --> 03:22.060
the old DeLacy to me, and by degrees to have discovered myself to the rest of his family,

03:22.620 --> 03:27.640
when they should have been prepared for my approach. But I did not believe my errors

03:27.640 --> 03:32.640
to be irretrievable, and after much consideration I resolved to return to the cottage, seek

03:32.640 --> 03:39.320
the old man, and by my representations win him to my party. These thoughts calmed me,

03:39.460 --> 03:45.560
and in the afternoon I sank into a profound sleep. But the fever of my blood did not allow

03:45.560 --> 03:53.000
me to be visited by peaceful dreams. The horrible scene of the preceding day was forever acting

03:53.000 --> 03:59.920
before my eyes. The females were flying and the enraged Felix tearing me from his father's

03:59.920 --> 04:07.600
feet. I awoke exhausted, and finding that it was already night, I crept forth from my

04:07.600 --> 04:14.060
hiding place and went in search of food. When my hunger was appeased, I directed my steps

04:14.060 --> 04:21.300
towards the well-known path that conducted to the cottage. All there was at peace. I

04:21.300 --> 04:26.160
crept into my hovel and remained in silent expectation of the accustomed hour when the

04:26.160 --> 04:34.680
family arose. That hour passed. The sun mounted high in the heavens, but the cottagers did

04:34.680 --> 04:42.840
not appear. I trembled violently, apprehending some dreadful misfortune. The inside of the

04:42.840 --> 04:48.880
cottage was dark, and I heard no motion. I cannot describe the agony of this suspense.

04:50.660 --> 04:56.140
Presently two countrymen passed by, but pausing near the cottage they entered into conversation

04:56.140 --> 05:01.720
using violent gesticulations. But I did not understand what they said as they spoke the

05:01.720 --> 05:08.100
language of the country, which differed from that of my protectors. Soon after, however,

05:08.880 --> 05:13.660
Felix approached with another man. I was surprised as I knew that he had not quitted the cottage

05:13.660 --> 05:18.940
that morning, and waited anxiously to discover from his discourse the meaning of these unusual

05:18.940 --> 05:19.400
appearances.

05:20.900 --> 05:25.720
"'Do you consider,' said his companion to him, "'that you will be obliged to pay three

05:25.720 --> 05:30.660
months' rent and to lose the produce of your garden? I do not wish to take any unfair advantage,

05:30.660 --> 05:34.240
and I beg, therefore, that you will take some days to consider of your determination.'

05:35.420 --> 05:41.420
"'It is utterly useless,' replied Felix. We can never again inhabit your cottage. The

05:41.420 --> 05:45.720
life of my father is in the greatest danger, going to the dreadful circumstances that I

05:45.720 --> 05:51.300
have related. My wife and my sister will never recover from their horror. I entreat

05:51.300 --> 05:57.460
you not to reason with me any more. Take possession of your tenement and let me fly from this

05:58.420 --> 06:03.560
place.' Felix trembled violently as he said this. He and his companion entered the cottage

06:03.560 --> 06:10.060
in which they remained for a few minutes, and then departed. I never saw any of the family

06:10.060 --> 06:11.180
of De Lacy more.

06:14.140 --> 06:19.900
I continued for the remainder of the day in my hovel in a state of utter and stupid despair.

06:21.260 --> 06:26.600
My protectors had departed and had broken the only link that held me to the world. For

06:26.600 --> 06:31.720
the first time the feelings of revenge and hatred filled my bosom, and I did not strive

06:31.720 --> 06:37.520
to control them. But allowing myself to be borne away by the stream, I bent my mind towards

06:37.520 --> 06:46.380
injury and death. When I thought of my friends, of the mild voice of De Lacy, the gentle eyes

06:46.380 --> 06:53.880
of Agatha, and the exquisite beauty of the Arabian, these thoughts vanished, and a gush

06:53.880 --> 07:02.660
of tears somewhat soothed me. But again, when I reflected that they had spurned and deserted

07:02.660 --> 07:11.800
me, anger returned, a rage of anger, and unable to injure anything human, I turned

07:11.800 --> 07:19.240
my fury towards inanimate objects. As night advanced I placed a variety of combustibles

07:19.240 --> 07:24.540
around the cottage, and after having destroyed every vestige of cultivation in the garden,

07:25.720 --> 07:30.560
I waited with forced impatience until the moon had sunk to commence my operations.

07:32.020 --> 07:37.680
As the night advanced a fierce wind arose from the woods and quickly dispersed the cloud

07:37.680 --> 07:44.220
that had loitered in the heavens. The blast tore along like a mighty avalanche and produced

07:44.220 --> 07:52.180
a kind of insanity in my spirits that burst all bounds of reason and reflection. I lighted

07:52.180 --> 07:58.840
the dry branch of a tree and danced with fury around the devoted cottage. My eyes still

07:58.840 --> 08:07.020
fixed on the western horizon, my brand. It sank, and with a loud scream I fired the straw

08:07.020 --> 08:14.160
and heath and bushes which I had collected. The wind fanned the fire, and the cottage

08:14.160 --> 08:20.940
was quickly enveloped by the flames, which clung to it and licked it with their forked

08:20.940 --> 08:27.860
and destroying tongues. As soon as I was convinced that no assistance could save any part of

08:27.860 --> 08:35.160
the habitation, I quitted the scene and sought for refuge in the woods. And now, with the

08:35.160 --> 08:42.440
world before me, whither should I bend my steps? I resolved to fly far from the scene

08:42.440 --> 08:55.720
of my misfortunes. But to me, hated and despised, every country must be equally horrible. At

08:55.720 --> 09:02.480
least my mind. I learned from your papers that you were my father, my creator, and to

09:02.480 --> 09:09.880
whom could I apply with more fitness than to him who had given me life. Among the lessons

09:09.880 --> 09:16.900
that Felix had bestowed upon Safi, geography had not been omitted. I had learned from these

09:16.900 --> 09:22.800
the relative situations of the different countries of the earth. You had mentioned Geneva as

09:22.800 --> 09:31.040
the name of your native town, and towards this place I resolved to proceed. But how

09:31.040 --> 09:35.900
was I to direct myself? I knew that I must travel in a southwesterly direction to reach

09:35.900 --> 09:41.260
my destination, but the sun was my only guide. I did not know the names of the towns that

09:41.260 --> 09:48.640
I was to pass through, nor could I ask information from a single human being. But I did not despair.

09:49.220 --> 09:55.760
From you only could I hope for Sukkur, although towards you I felt no sentiment, but that

09:55.760 --> 10:04.160
of hatred. Unfeeling, heartless creator! You had endowed me with perceptions and passions

10:04.160 --> 10:11.120
and then cast me abroad an object for the scorn and horror of mankind. But on you only

10:11.120 --> 10:18.060
had I any claim for pity and redress. And from you I determined to seek that justice

10:18.340 --> 10:25.860
which I vainly attempted to gain from any other being that wore the human form. My travels

10:25.860 --> 10:33.320
were long, and the sufferings I endured intense. It was late in autumn when I quitted the district

10:33.320 --> 10:39.800
where I had so long resided. I traveled only at night, fearful of encountering the visage

10:39.800 --> 10:48.040
of a human being. Nature decayed around me, and the sun became heatless. Rain and snow

10:48.040 --> 10:54.340
poured around me, mighty rivers were frozen, the surface of the earth was hard and chill

10:54.340 --> 11:04.420
and bare, and I found no shelter. Oh earth, how often did I implicate curses on the cause

11:04.420 --> 11:12.040
of my being! The mildness of my nature had fled, and all within me was turned to gall

11:12.040 --> 11:19.740
and bitterness. The nearer I approached your habitation, the more deeply did I feel the

11:19.740 --> 11:28.200
spirit of revenge enkindled in my heart. Snow fell, and the waters were hardened, but I

11:28.200 --> 11:34.040
rested not. A few incidents now and then directed me, and I possessed a map of the country.

11:34.880 --> 11:41.200
But I often wandered wide from my path. The agony of my feelings allowed me no respite,

11:41.200 --> 11:48.720
no incident occurred from which my rage and misery could not extract its food. But a circumstance

11:48.720 --> 11:53.600
that happened when I arrived on the confines of Switzerland, when the sun had recovered

11:53.600 --> 11:59.360
its warmth and the earth again began to look green, confirmed in a special manner the bitterness

11:59.900 --> 12:06.480
and horror of my feelings. I generally rested during the day and traveled only when I was

12:06.480 --> 12:12.260
secured by night from the view of man. One morning, however, finding that my path lay

12:12.260 --> 12:18.200
through a deep wood, I ventured to continue my journey after the sun had risen. The day,

12:18.200 --> 12:23.640
which was one of the first of spring, cheered even me by the loveliness of its sunshine

12:23.640 --> 12:30.600
and the bombiness of the air. I felt emotions of gentleness and pleasure that had long appeared

12:30.600 --> 12:38.500
dead revive within me. Half surprised by the novelty of these sensations, I allowed myself

12:38.500 --> 12:45.240
to be borne away by them, and forgetting my solitude and deformity, dared to be happy.

12:46.560 --> 12:54.290
Soft tears again bedewed my cheeks, and I even raised my humid eyes with thankfulness

12:55.050 --> 13:03.470
towards the blessed sun which bestowed such joy upon me. I continued to wind among the

13:03.470 --> 13:09.450
paths of the wood until I came to its boundary, which was skirted by a deep and rapid river

13:09.450 --> 13:16.090
into which many of the trees bent their branches, now budding with the fresh spring. Here I

13:16.090 --> 13:23.510
paused, not exactly knowing what path to pursue, when I heard the sound of voices that induced

13:23.510 --> 13:29.670
me to conceal myself under the shade of a cypress. I was scarcely hid when a young girl

13:29.670 --> 13:36.190
came running towards the spot where I was concealed laughing, as if she ran from someone

13:36.190 --> 13:41.610
in sport. She continued her course along the precipitous sides of the river when suddenly

13:41.610 --> 13:46.790
her foot slipped, and she fell into the rapid stream. I rushed from my hiding place and

13:46.790 --> 13:50.690
with extreme labor, from the force of the current, saved her and dragged her to shore.

13:51.490 --> 13:57.070
She was senseless, and I endeavored by every means in my power to restore animation the

13:57.070 --> 14:04.330
deeper parts of the woods. I followed speedily, I hardly knew why, but when the man saw me

14:04.330 --> 14:10.650
drew near, he aimed a gun, which he carried at my body and fired. I sank to the ground,

14:11.490 --> 14:20.670
and my injurer, with increased swiftness, escaped into the wood. This was then the reward

14:20.670 --> 14:27.630
of my benevolence. I had saved a human being from destruction, the feelings of kindness

14:27.630 --> 14:32.910
and gentleness which I had entertained, but a few moments before gave place to hellish

14:32.910 --> 14:41.970
rage and gnashing of teeth. Inflamed by pain, I vowed eternal hatred and vengeance to all

14:41.970 --> 14:50.650
mankind. But the agony of my wound overcame me. My pulses paused, and I fainted. I was

14:51.470 --> 14:56.950
for some weeks I led a miserable life in the woods, endeavoring to cure the wound which

14:56.950 --> 15:03.030
I had received. The ball had entered my shoulder, and I knew not whether it had remained there

15:03.030 --> 15:09.530
or passed through. At any rate, I had no means of extracting it. My sufferings were augmented

15:09.530 --> 15:20.110
also by the oppressive sense of the injustice and ingratitude of their infliction. My daily

15:20.110 --> 15:25.670
revenge, such as would alone compensate for the outrages and anguish I had endured.

15:27.290 --> 15:34.910
After some weeks my wound healed, and I continued my journey. The labors I endured were no longer

15:34.910 --> 15:41.250
to be alleviated by the bright sun or gentle breezes of spring. All joy was but a mockery

15:41.250 --> 15:46.910
which insulted my desolate state and made me feel more painfully that I was not made

15:46.910 --> 15:54.850
for the enjoyment of pleasure. But my toils now drew near a close, and in two months from

15:54.850 --> 16:01.850
this time I reached the environs of Geneva. It was evening when I arrived, and I retired

16:01.850 --> 16:06.990
to a hiding place among the fields that surround it to meditate in what manner I should apply

16:06.990 --> 16:13.450
to you. I was oppressed by fatigue and hunger and far too unhappy to enjoy the gentle breezes

16:13.450 --> 16:20.270
of evening or the prospect of the sun setting behind the stupendous mountains of Jura. At

16:20.270 --> 16:26.270
this time a slight sleep relieved me from the pain of reflection which was disturbed

16:26.270 --> 16:31.230
by the approach of a beautiful child, who came running into the recess I had chosen

16:31.230 --> 16:39.390
with all the sportiveness of infancy. Suddenly, as I gazed on him, an idea seized me that

16:39.390 --> 16:46.150
this little creature was unprejudiced and had lived too short a time to have imbibed

16:46.150 --> 16:53.690
a horror of deformity. If therefore I could seize him and educate him as my companion

16:53.690 --> 16:59.910
and friend, I should not be so desolate in this peopled earth. Urged by this impulse

16:59.910 --> 17:05.930
I seized on the boy as he passed and drew him towards me. As soon as he beheld my form

17:05.930 --> 17:10.290
he placed his hands before his eyes and uttered a shriek. I drew his hand forcibly from his

17:10.290 --> 17:14.530
face and said, Child, what is the meaning of this? I do not intend to hurt you. Listen

17:14.530 --> 17:22.350
to me. He struggled violently. Let me go, he cried. Monster! Ugly wretch! You wish to

17:22.350 --> 17:28.430
eat me and tear me to pieces. You are an ogre. Let me go or I will tell my papa. Boy, you

17:28.430 --> 17:33.890
will never see your father again. You must come with me. Hideous monster! Let me go.

17:34.240 --> 17:40.130
My papa is a syndic. He is Monsieur Frankenstein. He will punish you. You dare not keep me.

17:41.530 --> 17:48.810
Frankenstein! You belong then to my enemy. To him towards whom I have sworn eternal revenge

17:48.810 --> 17:54.990
you shall be my first victim. The child still struggled and loaded me with epithets which

17:54.990 --> 18:02.430
carried despair to my heart. I grasped his throat to silence him and in a moment he lay

18:02.430 --> 18:10.530
dead at my feet. I gazed on my victim and my heart swelled with exultation and hellish

18:10.530 --> 18:18.290
triumph. Clapping my hands, I exclaimed, I too can create desolation. My enemy is not

18:18.290 --> 18:24.830
invulnerable. This death will carry despair to him and a thousand other miseries shall

18:24.830 --> 18:26.650
torment and destroy him.

18:28.130 --> 18:36.350
As I fixed my eyes on the child, I saw something glittering on his breast. I took it. It was

18:36.350 --> 18:43.990
a portrait of a most lovely woman. In spite of my malignity, it softened and attracted

18:43.990 --> 18:50.970
me. For a few moments I gazed with delight on her dark eyes, fringed by dark lashes and

18:50.970 --> 18:58.570
her lovely lips. But presently my rage returned. I remembered that I was forever deprived of

18:58.570 --> 19:02.750
the delights that such beautiful creatures could bestow and that she whose resemblance

19:02.750 --> 19:09.690
I contemplated would, in regarding me, have changed that air of divine benignity to one

19:09.690 --> 19:11.810
expressive of disgust and of fright.

19:13.830 --> 19:20.090
Can you wonder that such thoughts transported me with rage? I only wonder that at that moment,

19:20.570 --> 19:25.650
instead of venting my sensations and exclamations and agony, I did not rush among mankind and

19:25.650 --> 19:31.110
perish in the attempt to destroy them. While I was overcome by these feelings, I left the

19:31.110 --> 19:36.210
spot where I had committed the murder, and seeking a more secluded hiding-place, I entered

19:36.210 --> 19:43.630
a barn which had appeared to me to be empty. A woman was sleeping on some straw. She was

19:43.630 --> 19:49.970
young, not indeed so beautiful as her whose portrait I held, but of an agreeable aspect

19:49.970 --> 19:56.130
and blooming in the loveliness of youth and health. Here, I thought, is one of those whose

19:56.130 --> 20:03.130
joy-emparting smiles are bestowed on all but me. And then I bent over her and whispered,

20:04.850 --> 20:13.310
Awake, fairest, thy lover is near. He would give his life but to obtain one look of affection

20:13.310 --> 20:17.650
from thine eyes. My beloved, awake!

20:18.970 --> 20:26.090
The sleeper stirred. A thrill of terror ran through me. Should she indeed awake and see

20:26.090 --> 20:32.530
me and curse me and denounce the murderer? Thus would she assuredly act if her darkened

20:32.530 --> 20:39.870
eyes opened and she beheld me. The thought was madness. It stirred from the fiend within

20:39.870 --> 20:47.630
me. Not I, but she shall suffer. The murder I have committed because I am forever robbed

20:47.630 --> 20:56.610
of all that she could give me, she shall atone. The crime had its source in her. Be hers

20:56.610 --> 20:57.490
the punishment.

20:59.540 --> 21:06.030
Thanks to the lessons of Felix and the sanguinary laws of man, I had learned now to work mischief.

21:06.850 --> 21:14.570
I bent over her and placed the portrait securely in one of the folds of her dress. She moved

21:14.570 --> 21:17.030
again and I fled.

21:19.630 --> 21:24.850
For some days I haunted the spot where these scenes had taken place, sometimes wishing

21:24.850 --> 21:31.290
to see you, sometimes resolved to quit the world and its miseries forever. At length

21:31.290 --> 21:37.990
I wandered towards these mountains and have ranged through their immense recesses consumed

21:37.990 --> 21:45.610
by a burning passion which you alone can gratify. We may not part until you have promised to

21:45.610 --> 21:54.290
comply with my requisition. I am alone and miserable. Man will not associate with me,

21:54.710 --> 22:02.950
but one as deformed and horrible as myself would not deny herself to me. My companion

22:02.950 --> 22:09.430
must be of the same species and have the same defects. This being you must create.

